Plants absorb water because of water potential. Water goes from high water potential to low water potential. Stuff like temprature, pressure, and osmolarity effect water potential. So soda in an open container at room temprature would have lower  water potential then distilled water in an open container at room temprature. So if you want something that can water a plant you have to make sure it has a higher water potential then the cells in the plant. That's why saltwater generally makes you more thirsty because it has a lower water potential then your cells and is actually sucking the water from your cells. Water potential is also why plants get all droopy when you forget to water them, they don't have enough water in their cells to remain rigid.
